In plants, leaf and wood traits co-vary along gradients that range from acquisitive (fast) growth strategies to more conservative (slow) growth strategies (\ref{fig:concept}) \citep{Westoby1998,Westoby2006,Wright2004,Chave2009,Diaz2016}. These global relationships are the foundation of the leaf economic spectrum and the wood economic spectrum \citep{Wright2004,Chave2009}, but are limited in their ability to predict how variable traits are \citep{Violle2012}. As a result, highly variable traits like phenology are often excluded from trait studies, leaving the relationships between broader trait syndromes and phenology largely unknown, while many studies simply assume this variability to be negligible \citep{Grime2006,Pau2011}\\

What research has been done to explore the relationship between phenology and broader trait syndromes has mostly focused on intra-specific trait variability within a growing season. This works highlights the importance of accounting for phenology when collecting trait data, demonstrating the potential for traits, and correlations between traits, to vary within a growing season relative to phenological stages \citep{McKown2013, Fajardo2016}. But only a handful of studies have explicitly studied phenology-trait relationships in the context of phenological responses to climate change or environmental cues. Recent work by \cite[Sporbert et al.][]{Sporbert2022} conducted across European botanical gardens, however, found evidence of relationships between woody plant vegetative stages and traits such as height and leaf area, with taller trees exhibiting delays in phenology relative to short species. But the generality of these trends and whether they persist under natural conditions, is less clear.\\

