We combined the species-level trait estimates with data on forcing, chilling and photoperiod values from the OSPREE database of phenological experiments  in order to test if traits (height, SLA, seed mass, LNC) related to phenological cues and species budburst dates (Fig. \ref{fig:slopes}). For some traits we did find traits to relate to variation in phenological cues across species, with some species exhibiting stronger or weaker responses (as illustrated conceptually in Fig \ref{fig:slopes}a and c), while traits were weak predictors for other species (Fig \ref{fig:slopes}b).\\

Across traits, height, SLA, and LNC strongly predicted responses to different cue-levels (($\beta_{\text{chill[sp]}}$, $\beta_{\text{force[sp]}}$, and $\beta_{\text{photo[sp]}}$, Fig \ref{fig:cuetraits} a-i), but only showed consistent directions of responses across cues for LNC (Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits} j-l). As we predicted, height was related to chilling and photoperiod cues, with taller species having larger responses with stronger cues (\Sexpr{htBCSpMean} m per standardized chilling; 90\% uncertainty interval (UI): \Sexpr{lower_htBCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_htBCSpMean} and \Sexpr{htBPSpMean} m per standardized photoperiod; 90\% UI: \Sexpr{lower_htBPSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_htBPSpMean}, Fig \ref{fig:cuetraits} a-c). As illustrated for the characteristically acquisitive species, \emph{Alnus incana}, and conservative species, \emph(Aesculus hippocastanum) (Fig \ref{fig:slopesSupp}), this response to chilling and photoperiod cues leads to later budburst ($\mu_{pheno}$), and therefore fits within an overall conservative growth strategy. Seed mass, however, had the weakest responses, with no considerable relationship between seed mass and cues across the three cues (Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits} g-i \& Fig \ref{fig:slopesSupp}). \\

Of our leaf traits, we found species SLA to relate to photoperiod (\Sexpr{slaBPSpMean} mm\textsuperscript{2}/mg per standardized photoperiod; 90\% UI: \Sexpr{lower_slaBPSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_slaBPSpMean}, Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits} f), but did not strongly predict responses to chilling or forcing (Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits} d and e). Thus, species with more acquisitive growth strategies (thin leaves and a lower investment in leaf mass that leads to high SLA values), had larger responses to photoperiod cues, contrary to our predictions (Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits} d and e). For LNC, we found that species that produce leaves with high nitrogen content, which relates generally to high photosynthetic rates and acquisitive growth, show weak responses to cues (Fig. \ref{fig:cuetraits} j-i). These findings are in line with our predictions that high LNC species (acquisitive) would be less responsive to chilling (\Sexpr{lncBCSpMean} mg/g per standardized chilling; 90\% UI: \Sexpr{lower_lncBCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lncBCSpMean}), but we found similar responses to photoperiod (\Sexpr{lncBPSpMean} mg/g per standardized photoperiod; 90\% UI: \Sexpr{lower_lncBPSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lncBPSpMean}) and to forcing cues (\Sexpr{lncBFSpMean} mg/g per standardized forcing; 90\% UI: \Sexpr{lower_lncBFSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lncBFSpMean}, Fig \ref{fig:cuetraits} j-i). 
