\subsection*{Effects of phenology-trait relationships on community assembly} 

In our study of temperate forest communities, the relationships between budburst phenology and other plant traits provided insights into the mechanisms that shape species phenotypes. Earlier budbursting species had traits, such as shorter heights and low LNC, that allow them to grow quickly and benefit from greater light availability in the open canopy of many early-spring temperate forests. This phenotype can be linked to other ecological processes and species characteristics, such as species successional position, as illustrated by the differences between early and late successional species, like \emph{Alnus incana} and \emph{Quercus rubra} (Fig \ref{fig:cuetraits}). Our results may also be useful to help predict communities' potential for invasion, as communities with similar phenologies and suites of traits, appear more susceptible to fast growing, non-native species \citep{Wolkovich2011,Alexander2019,Schuster2021}. In identifying the trait syndromes of native forest communities and the interactions between traits and environmental cues, we can better predict how changes in environmental cues will alter species growth strategies and productivity, identifying species most likely to be negatively impacted by future climates and in need of mitigation and conservation efforts. \\
